<p>The mid-year follow-up draw covers approximately 60 of the highest-priority markers &#8212; the cardiovascular, metabolic, inflammatory, and hormonal set that moves meaningfully in response to lifestyle and supplement interventions. It does not repeat the full panel.</p>

<div class="callout">
<div class="callout-label">Why the second draw matters</div>
<p>Most biomarker services test you once per year. Function&#8217;s mid-year draw is the only way to answer the question that matters most: did the intervention work? If your first draw showed elevated <a href="/biomarkers/apob">ApoB</a> and low <a href="/biomarkers/vitamin-d">Vitamin D</a>, and you spent six months adjusting your diet and supplementing &#8212; the mid-year draw tells you whether it moved. That test-intervene-retest loop is what preventive medicine is actually supposed to do.</p>
</div>
</div>

<div class="content-section">
<h2>The platform experience</h2>
<p>Function&#8217;s dashboard is polished and well-organized &#8212; results are grouped by category with clear flagging, per-marker explanations, and recommended next steps. The desktop and mobile app experience is consistently praised for being clean and non-overwhelming given the volume of data.</p>
<p>The AI protocol builder, introduced in early 2026, generates a full-body optimization plan from your biomarker profile, health goals, and stated preferences. Compared to Superpower&#8217;s more mature AI chat, Function&#8217;s AI feels slightly less conversational in early reviews &#8212; but the protocol generation feature is a meaningful addition that is being actively developed.</p>
<p>One notable limitation: Function does not allow historical lab data import. If you have years of prior bloodwork, you cannot integrate it into your Function dashboard &#8212; you start fresh. Superpower&#8217;s &#8220;Bring Your Own Data&#8221; feature handles this and it&#8217;s a real advantage for users with an established testing history.</p>
</div>

<div class="content-section">
<h2>Pricing history &#8212; and the loyalty controversy</h2>
<p>Function launched at $499/year. In late 2025, facing competition from Superpower ($199) and Empirical Health ($190), Function reduced pricing to $365/year for new members. The rollout was initially botched &#8212; existing members were initially told they would continue paying $499 while new members got the lower rate. The backlash on Reddit was swift and pointed; Function ultimately addressed the disparity, though early adopters were understandably frustrated.</p>
<p>At $365/year, the value proposition is meaningfully improved. Two draws at 160+ markers works out to roughly $1.40 per marker per draw &#8212; substantially cheaper than ordering equivalent tests piecemeal through à la carte services.</p>
</div>

